as independently. Previous studies of gender in medieval Ireland have emphasized sexism and sex-segregated celibacy, dismissing abundant evidence of alternative approaches throughout the sources, including in the Lives of Ireland’s female saints. Sacred Sisters places these generally marginalized texts at its center, exploring their portraits of empowered, authoritative, compassionate women who exemplified an accepting and affirming ethics of gender and sexuality that would be unusual in many mainstream Christian movements in the present day, let alone in the Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aSaintszIreland. 0aWomen in ChristianityzIreland. 0aWomen saintszIreland. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aReligion and Theology. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aSaints, Gender, Medieval Sexuality, Ireland, hagiography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048542994zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048542994423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048542994/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK P